"Chang M.B., Lee H.M.","Abatement of perfluorocarbons with combined plasma catalysis in atmospheric-pressure environment",2004,"Catalysis Today","89","1-2",,"109","115",,,10.1016/j.cattod.2003.11.016,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0842329913&partnerID=40&md5=8e06adb87780ee225ab17e94aa04306f","Grad. Inst. of Environ. Engineering, National Central University, Chung-Li 320, Taiwan","Chang, M.B., Grad. Inst. of Environ. Engineering, National Central University, Chung-Li 320, Taiwan; Lee, H.M., Grad. Inst. of Environ. Engineering, National Central University, Chung-Li 320, Taiwan","Perfluorocarbons (PFCs) are widely used in semiconductor industry. However, they intensely absorb infrared radiation and consequently aggravate the greenhouse effect. A combined plasma catalysis (CPC) technology is developed to destroy PFCs. For practical purpose the CPC is designed to function at room temperature and atmospheric pressure. In addition, this study compares three kinds of operations, i.e. catalysis, plasmas and CPC. Results indicate that CPC achieves the highest PFC destruction efficiency. Complete destructions are achieved for SF6 and NF3. Removal efficiencies for CF 4 and C2F6 are 66 and 83%, respectively. The products formed in CPC process for CF4 and C2F 6 are mainly CO2 and a little CO. In contrast, the products formed in plasma process include CO2, CO, COF2, and CF4. In brief, this study demonstrates that CPC is of a higher efficiency and less-toxic products for PFC removal compared with plasma technology at the given conditions. © 2003 Elsevier B.V. All rights reserved.","Air pollution control technology; Combined plasma catalysis (CPC); Global warming; Perfluorocarbons (PFCs)","Adsorption; Air pollution control; Catalysis; Chemical bonds; Dissociation; Global warming; Greenhouse effect; Health; Methane; Oxidation; Plasmas; Rate constants; Semiconductor devices; Air pollution control technology; Combined plasma catalysis (CPC); Perfluorocarbons (PFC); Carbon",,,,,,"Beu, L., Brown, P.T., (1998) Proceedings of the IEEE/CPMT International Electronics Manufacturing Technology Symposium, pp. 277-285; Feaver, W.B., Rossin, J.A., (1999) Catal. Today, 54, p. 13; Windawi, H., Wyatt, M., (1993) Plat. Met. Rev., 37, p. 186; Imamura, S., (1992) Catal. Today, 11, p. 547; Farris, M.M., Klinghoffer, A.A., Rossin, J.A., Tevault, D.E., (1992) Catal. Today, 11, p. 501; Fan, J., Yates, J.T., (1994) J. Phys. Chem., 98, p. 10621; Karmakar, S., Greene, H.L., (1995) J. Catal., 151, p. 394; Brown, R.S., Rossin, J.A., Aitchison, K., (2001) Solid State Technol., 44, p. 189; Kiplinger, J., Richmond, L., Osterberg, C., (1994) Chem. Rev., 94, p. 373; Chen, D.T., David, M.M., Tiers, G.V.D., Schroepfer, J.N., (1998) Environ. Sci. Technol., 32, p. 3237; Chang, J.S., Kostov, K.G., Urashima, K., Yamamoto, T., Okayasu, Y., Kato, Y., Iwaizumi, T., Yoshimura, K., (2000) IEEE Trans. Ind. Appl., 36, p. 1251; Wofford, B.A., Jackson, M.W., Hartz, C., Bevan, J.W., (1999) Environ. Sci. Technol., 33, p. 1892; Chang, M.B., Yu, S.J., (2001) Environ. Sci. Technol., 35, p. 1587; Yu, S.J., Chang, M.B., (2001) Plasma Chem. Plasma Proc., 21, p. 311; Makkee, M., Wiersma, A., Van de Sandt, E.J.A.X., (2000) Catal. Today, 55, p. 125; Lieberman, M.A., Lichtenberg, A.J., (1994) Principle of Plasma Discharges and Materials Processing, pp. 497-502. , Wiley, New York; Bond, G.C., (1990) Heterogeneous Catalysis: Principles and Applications, 2nd Ed., p. 46. , Clarendon Press, Oxford; Houghton, J.T., Meira Filho, L.G., Callander, B.A., Harris, N., Kattenberg, A., Maskell, K., (1996) Climate Change 1995 - The Science of Climate Change, p. 121. , Cambridge University Press, New York","Chang, M.B.; Grad. Inst. of Environ. Engineering, National Central University, Chung-Li 320, Taiwan; email: mbchang@ncuen.ncu.edu.tw",,,,,,,,09205861,,CATTE,,"English","Catal Today",Conference Paper,Scopus,2-s2.0-0842329913
